<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="264" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,607,1282]" pageId="4" pageNumber="264">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1039,1065]" pageId="4" pageNumber="264">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is poorly known. We collected several specimens from 
<collectingRegion box="[1104,1171,1039,1065]" country="China" name="Hebei" pageId="4" pageNumber="264">Hebei</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[1229,1406,1039,1066]" country="China" name="Nei Mongol" pageId="4" pageNumber="264">Inner Mongolia</collectingRegion>
in recent years, and found that this species shows variation in elytral pattern, with four black spots in most specimens but only two spots or uniformly yellow-brown in a few cases.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,607,1282]" pageId="4" pageNumber="264">
<bibRefCitation author="Reitter, E." box="[199,358,1147,1173]" pageId="4" pageNumber="264" refId="ref28337" refString="Reitter, E. (1911) Fauna Germanica. Die Kafer des Deutschen Reiches. Vol. 3. Lutz, Stuttgart, 436 pp., 48 pls." type="book" year="1911">Reitter (1911)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Reitter (HNHM" authorityYear="1911" box="[484,734,1147,1173]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Schroetteria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="264" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subpolita">
<emphasis box="[484,734,1147,1173]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="264">Schroetteria subpolita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Northeast 
<collectingCountry box="[925,992,1147,1173]" name="China" pageId="4" pageNumber="264">China</collectingCountry>
(old name “Mandschuria”) and distinguished it from 
<taxonomicName box="[331,434,1183,1209]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Schrotteria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="264" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="polita">
<emphasis box="[331,434,1183,1209]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="264">M. polita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
mainly by the slightly bulging temples and the punctures on the body. However, according to our specimens, we think that these features correspond to intraspecific variation. Therefore, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Reitter (HNHM" authorityYear="1911" box="[1275,1409,1219,1245]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Schroetteria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="264" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subpolita">
<emphasis box="[1275,1409,1219,1245]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="264">S. subpolita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is considered a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Motschulsky" authorityYear="1845" box="[513,626,1255,1281]" class="Insecta" family="Brentidae" genus="Megatrachelus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="264" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="politus">
<emphasis box="[513,626,1255,1281]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="264">M. politus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
